        <section id="section1">
            <h2>1. Understanding the Political-Tech Landscape</h2>
            <p>The political landscape has evolved with the involvement of tech giants and their growing influence on governance. This section delves into the key aspects of these alliances and how they shape public policy.</p>
            <h3>1.1 The Role of Project 25</h3>
            <p>Project 25 is a significant initiative aimed at solidifying political power through legislative and executive channels. Understanding its framework helps in identifying how tech and political interests align to shape policy.</p>
            <p>Resources:</p>
            <ul class="resource-list">
                <li><a href="https://www.propublica.org" target="_blank">ProPublica: Investigative Reports on Political Influence</a></li>
                <li><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/us" target="_blank">The Guardian: U.S. Politics Coverage</a></li>
            </ul>
            <h3>1.2 Tech Billionaires' Influence</h3>
            <p>Leading figures in the tech industry often use their platforms to influence public policy. This can include campaign financing, data-driven AI strategies, and shaping narratives through social media.</p>
            <p>Resources:</p>
            <ul class="resource-list">
                <li><a href="https://www.eff.org" target="_blank">Electronic Frontier Foundation: Digital Rights and Tech Power</a></li>
                <li><a href="https://www.cfr.org" target="_blank">Council on Foreign Relations: Technology and Power Dynamics</a></li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="section2">
            <h2>2. Legal Ways to Resist and Advocate</h2>
            <p>Engaging in lawful activism is an effective way to combat undue influence. This section outlines practical strategies for community involvement and policy advocacy.</p>
            <h3>2.1 Community Outreach and Public Education</h3>
            <p>Hosting workshops and town hall meetings can raise awareness about the intersection of politics and technology. Use these gatherings to educate the public on the importance of transparency and ethical governance.</p>
            <p>Resources:</p>
            <ul class="resource-list">
                <li><a href="https://www.aclu.org" target="_blank">ACLU: Resources for Civic Engagement</a></li>
                <li><a href="https://www.commoncause.org" target="_blank">Common Cause: Advocating for Open Democracy</a></li>
            </ul>
            <a href="https://www.commoncause.org" target="_blank" class="cta-button">Join an Advocacy Group</a>
            <h3>2.2 Participating in Policy Discussions</h3>
            <p>Citizens can voice their opinions during public consultations and legislative review processes. Submitting comments and feedback helps shape policy in favor of democracy.</p>
            <p>Resources:</p>
            <ul class="resource-list">
                <li><a href="https://www.regulations.gov" target="_blank">Regulations.gov: Public Comments Portal</a></li>
                <li><a href="https://www.congress.gov" target="_blank">Congress.gov: Legislative Process and Updates</a></li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="section3">
            <h2>3. Digital Literacy and Civic Engagement</h2>
            <p>Improving digital literacy helps citizens critically evaluate information and recognize disinformation. This section provides resources and strategies for fostering informed civic participation.</p>
            <h3>3.1 Hosting Workshops and Training Sessions</h3>
            <p>Offer training on recognizing media bias, verifying sources, and understanding how algorithms may manipulate information delivery.</p>
            <p>Resources:</p>
            <ul class="resource-list">
                <li><a href="https://www.newslit.org" target="_blank">The News Literacy Project: Resources for Educators</a></li>
                <li><a href="https://www.factcheck.org" target="_blank">FactCheck.org: Verifying Claims</a></li>
            </ul>
            <h3>3.2 Collaborating with Educational Institutions</h3>
            <p>Partnering with schools and universities to include digital literacy programs in curricula ensures students understand the impact of digital media and algorithms.</p>
            <h3>3.3 Digital Toolkits</h3>
            <p>Create downloadable toolkits that include guidelines and resources for assessing online content. These toolkits should offer step-by-step advice for identifying misinformation.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="section4">
            <h2>4. Leveraging AI and Digital Tools for Resistance</h2>
            <p>AI can be harnessed not just for political influence but also for supporting democratic efforts. Learn how to develop or use existing tools that promote transparency.</p>
            <h3>4.1 Developing Counter-Tools</h3>
            <p>Work with tech communities to build open-source projects that analyze and report biases in media content.</p>
            <p>Resources:</p>
            <ul class="resource-list">
                <li><a href="https://www.opensource.com" target="_blank">Open Source Projects for Civic Tech</a></li>
